functions -
            it is a reusable block of code, it take input parameters and perform logic and return single value
- functions are used for reusability ,easy maintenance, 
    function = input -> logic process -> output(single value)

types : 
        1. Inbuilt functions 
            string, numneric, date, aggregate, conversion functions
        2.user defined functions
            1.scalar function - returns one value per row
            2.Table function - returns a table (multiple rows/ columns)

Rules :
        1.must return only one value
        2. can't perform 
            insert
            update
            delete
            merge


---> difference between snowflake function and oracle function

- both are reuasble objects 
- but implementation ,and usage is difference
- oracle works pl/sql only
- snowflake works modern languages

snowflake function-
            create or replace function get_bonus(salary number)
            returns number
             as
             $$
                salary * 0.10
            $$;
 
--- $$ - it is delimeter
- used to mark the start and end of the function in body it tells where logic begin and end.
     

calling function :
                    select get_bonus(50000);

Example Oracle -
            create or replace function get_bonus(salary number)
            returns number
            is
            begin
                return salary * 0.10;
            end;

--> procedural (begin , end , return)

calling function :
                    select get_bonus(50000) from dual;

 --> dual is a dummy table in oracle , used only for syntax purpose.






 ----------------- Procedures-------------------

 store procedure -  it is a reusable block of code, it take input and perform multiple operations then return a value

 example procedure -

                create or replace procedure insert_employee(id int, name string)
                returns string
                language sql
                as
                $$
                begin
                    insert into employee values (:id, :name);
                    return 'Data Inserted';
                end;
                $$;


call procedure -
                    call insert_employee(1,'Guru');

    
    --> it take input and insert data into table then return msg.

